{{Use British English|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Amazon Watershed | image = File:Amazon Watershed.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[George Monbiot]] | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | release_number = | subjects = [[Deforestation]], [[Amazon Basin|The Amazon]], [[Logging]] | set_in = | published = [[London]] | publisher = Michael Joseph | publisher2 = Abacus (1992) | pub_date = 1991 | media_type = Print (paperback) | pages = 374 | awards = | isbn = 0349101620 | oclc = | dewey = | preceded_by = [[Poisoned Arrows: An investigative journey through the forbidden lands of West Papua]] }}
'''''Amazon Watershed : the new environmental investigation''''' is a 1991 book by British writer and environmental and political activist, [[George Monbiot]].
==Synopsis== The book is an investigation into the expulsion of peasants from their homes and their forced relocation to the [[Amazon Basin|Amazon]]. Military police attempt to kill Monbiot as he exposes a vast military project opening up the area to logging and deforestation. He tracks timber cut illegally from Indian reserves all the way back to retailers in the United Kingdom. According to the publishers, Monbiot also "examines the role of the British and American governments in promoting, wittingly or otherwise, this great ecological catastrophe".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monbiot.com/books/amazon-watershed/|title=Amazon Watershed|accessdate=19 August 2015|website=Monbiot.com}}</ref>
==Reception== The book won the [[Natural World Book Prize]], described as "the premier environmental book prize in the UK" in 1991.
