{{Infobox galaxy | name = [[New General Catalogue|NGC]] 169 | epoch = [[J2000]] | ra = {{RA|00|36|51.6}}<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for NGC 0169 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=NGC+169&img_stamp=yes&extend=no | accessdate=2016-09-02}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|+23|59|27}}<ref name="ned" /> | constellation name = [[Andromeda (constellation)|Andromeda]] | z = 0.015434<ref name="ned" /> | dist_ly = | type = SA(s)ab<ref name="ned" /> | appmag_v = 13.3<ref name="ned" /> | size_v = 2.6' &times; 0.7'<ref name="ned" /> | notes = | names = [[Uppsala General Catalogue|UGC]] 365, [[Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 2202, [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies|Arp]] 282<ref name="ned" /> }}
'''NGC 169''' is a [[barred spiral galaxy]] located in the constellation [[Andromeda (constellation)|Andromeda]]. It was discovered on September 18, 1857 by R. J. Mitchell.<ref>{{cite web|title=New General Catalog Objects: NGC 150 - 199|url=http://cseligman.com/text/atlas/ngc1a.htm#169|publisher=Cseligman|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>
NGC 169 has a smaller companion named NGC 169A. The two are currently [[interacting galaxy|interacting]], and the pair is included in [[Halton Arp]]'s [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Arp|first=Halton|title=Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies|publisher=[[California Institute of Technology]]|location=Pasadena, California|year=1966|url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/level5/Arp/Arp_contents.html|accessdate=5 Jan 2010}} (webpage includes PDF link)</ref>
